I just finished the MVP for my first Flatiron portfolio project, the CLI Data Gem project. Or rather, I’m mostly done. All the basic functionality is working, but there are a few final edits I want to make before submitting. Then, I have a whole list of other features I want to build that will have to wait for the future. But, I’m starting with an MVP. As a former Product Manager, I’m very familiar with the dangers of scope creep. Yet, it is oh so hard not to listen to the voice in my head itching to build something just a little bit better than it already is. 

I was really excited to start on our first portfolio project. Part of why I want to be a software engineer is that I love building and creating things. The CLI Data Gem project is meant to demonstrate our comprehension of object oriented programming in Ruby as well as basic API and/or web scraping concepts. I didn’t just want to build something that demonstrates my knowledge, though. I wanted to build something that would actually be useful to me (and hopefully others). 

One of the most pertinent pain points I expect to deal with soon is looking for work. I’ve been told multiple times how important networking is to finding a job. My first idea was to scrape information about my first connections on Linkedin, specifically where they work, and simultaneously scrape job postings from a job aggregator so I could cross reference the two and highlight companies with jobs openings that also have employees who are people I know. I quickly learned that [Linkedin purposefully makes it very difficult to scrape their site](https://www.bestproxyreviews.com/how-to-scrape-linkedin-using-proxies/). They have an API, but it is a very restrictive API. While not impossible to do, it’s probably a little past my current skill level, and I’m not ready yet to get sued by Linkedin.

My second idea was job-search related but more focused on quickly learning about companies I apply to. In particular, I’m interested in learning about the remote-work policy and culture of potential employers. I live in Albuquerque, NM. The tech scene is not that big here, and I expect to apply for a lot of remote positions. In the past, I’ve looked at sites that aggregate companies that operate remotely. However, these lists aren’t very comprehensive, and they don’t include information about changing circumstances due to Covid. It’s possible to do Google or DuckDuckGo searches about “remote work in tech”, but I’d have to read through a lot of articles to find the specific information I’m looking for.

After I realized the Linkedin scraper idea wasn’t going to work, I started looking for public APIs with good data. I found a good compilation on [github](https://github.com/public-apis/public-apis). After looking through them, I settled on The Guardian API. It is well documented, and I devised a way for it to help me solve my pain point of quickly learning about a company’s remote-work policy. I realized I could search through The Guardian’s trove of articles and then scrape the return articles for snippets of information related to the company I want to know more about. For example, I can get all Guardian articles with the keywords “tech”, “remote”, and “jobs.” Then, using a Regex pattern, I can return a snippet of the first couple of sentences before and after a company name, like “Google.” That way, I can quickly get a sense of what is being said about Google’s remote work policy in the news.

I also liked this idea because it’s very extensible. It could theoretically be used to quickly glean information about any topic. I could also extend it to other sources beyond The Guardian. I know the New York Times also has an API, and I’m guessing there are plenty of other blogs and new sources that don’t have as restrictive a scraping policy as Linkedin. But, back to the MVP.

The two biggest risks to the project were making sure I could get the API and Scraper interfaces to work as needed. So I focused there first. I started building an ApiResponse class and played around with Ruby’s pry gem to look at what the API returned and which data fields I’d want. However, I started realizing that some of that would depend on what I wanted the user experience to be like. I took a step back and finished drawing a workflow and writing out a user story.

I found it helpful to code in order of this flow. It helped provide me the context to know what methods to build and a rough idea of what their input and output should be. I built out some of the initial prompts in the Cli Class, fleshed out the ApiResponse class, built the Article class, and moved on from there. I did jump ahead to the Scraper class in between, just to make sure it was possible to scrape what I needed to. One of the hardest parts was actually figuring out the right Regex expression to return a text snippet containing the sentences before and after a search keyword. But, Google is my friend, and luckily there was some good advice on how to represent all the possible characters in a sentence. 

From ideation to MVP completion, this project took me about two and half days. Now, I’m cleaning up the code, and I might try my hands at writing tests. I haven’t written test for my code before, and I want to learn how. My CLI data gem is called News Search CLI (better name suggestions are welcome). You can find the code at https://github.com/charlie763/news_search_cli. Feedback is welcome. Enjoy!
